  "content": "ID: T1552.004\nTitle: Unsecured Credentials:Private Keys\nURL: https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1552/004\nAdversaries may search for private key certificate files on compromised systems for insecurely stored credentials. Private cryptographic keys and certificates are used for authentication, encryption/decryption, and digital signatures. [1] Common key and certificate file extensions include: .key, .pgp, .gpg, .ppk., .p12, .pem, .pfx, .cer, .p7b, .asc. Adversaries may also look in common key directories, such as ~/.ssh for SSH keys on * nix-based systems or C:\\Users\\(username)\\.ssh\\ on Windows. Adversary tools may also search compromised systems for file extensions relating to cryptographic keys and certificates. [2] [3] When a device is registered to Entra ID, a device key and a transport key are generated and used to verify the device’s identity. [4] An adversary with access to the device may be able to export the keys in order to impersonate the device. [5] On network devices, private keys may be exported via Network Device CLI commands such as crypto pki export . [6] Some private keys require a password or passphrase for operation, so an adversary may also use Input Capture for keylogging or attempt to Brute Force the passphrase off-line. These private keys can be used to authenticate to Remote Services like SSH or for use in decrypting other collected files such as email.",
  "category": "Article",
  "source": "Local Storage",
